      <title>I’m happy to announce BASTARDS will be published in the US and Canada by @semiot...</title>
      <link>https://www.instagram.com/p/DWTr2FVjeQ5/</link>
      <description><![CDATA[<p><img src="https://scontent-cph2-1.cdninstagram.com/v/t51.82787-15/656474805_18587750680057228_6664807496794284211_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_e35_tt6&amp;_nc_cat=104&amp;ig_cache_key=Mzg2MDYyMjEzODE2ODY5NzkxMw%3D%3D.3-ccb7-5&amp;ccb=7-5&amp;_nc_sid=58cdad&amp;efg=eyJ2ZW5jb2RlX3RhZyI6InhwaWRzLjExMjZ4MTA4NC5zZHIuQzMifQ%3D%3D&amp;_nc_ohc=TmuebvSZ7d0Q7kNvwHuunGl&amp;_nc_oc=AdpE4IfKEjK1_21vWoEyOKKI8qQijWvVLOfnRyPv4yUNE_q3DtsjxyfnxPJYabbRHks&amp;_nc_ad=z-m&amp;_nc_cid=0&amp;_nc_zt=23&amp;se=7&amp;_nc_ht=scontent-cph2-1.cdninstagram.com&amp;_nc_gid=gasANtv10cnKzYTbI_Jbhw&amp;_nc_ss=7a3ba&amp;oh=00_Afznhh5Xlmglx00epEQ83z5xZytnEDlUltQNvSa0TxT2RQ&amp;oe=69CA1B54" alt="Instagram billede fra @semiotexte" /></p><p><strong>@semiotexte</strong></p><p>I’m happy to announce BASTARDS will be published in the US and Canada by @semiotexte on September 29.  Available for preorder now.  For review copies contact info@semiotexte.com <br/>
<br/>
*<br/>
<br/>
Nate Lippens is the author of the acclaimed novels MY DEAD BOOK, a finalist for the Republic of Consciousness Prize, and RIPCORD, a New Statesman Book of the Year. He completes his Wisconsin trilogy with BASTARDS, a book of losses, memories, and survival.<br/>
<br/>
*<br/>
<br/>
Recently sprung from a stint on a psychiatric ward, the narrator of BASTARDS works hard to perform at being a person while questioning the concept of identity and what it means to be an aging working-class gay man when the word queer has become so elastic and gentrified it’s used to conservative ends. Struggling to survive, pay rent, and navigate a hostile world, he takes solace in art and his friends and measures what makes a life.<br/>
<br/>
Borrowing from the tropes of fragmented lyric essays, New Narrative, autofiction, and transgressive literature, Lippens is a bricoleur who creates a confected new form in his short novels. Queer pessimism in the age of affirmation. A search for something honest. An old queen’s cackle.<br/>
<br/>
*<br/>
<br/>
“I can’t say enough about how good Nate Lippens’s books are” Gary Indiana<br/>
<br/>
“Nate Lippens is a brilliant writer, and a much-needed voice among the new crop of queer novelists. His portrayals of working-class queers, ex-members of the queercore movement, recovering addicts, and artists, feels new, though somehow also a part of a nearly lost family of queer thinkers: the writers and artists his characters still cherish.” Chicago Review of Books<br/>
<br/>
“His bracing novels represent an honest reckoning with the post-AIDS era and its effect on life and imagination.” The Nation<br/>
<br/>
“What a gift to encounter such intelligent homosexuality!” Robert Glück<br/>
<br/>
*<br/>
<br/>
Cover image: Ray Dean, ‘Derek Jarman in Islington’, 1968. Courtesy the artist.</p>]]></description>
