mp;_nc_gid=gasANtv10cnKzYTbI_Jbhw&amp;_nc_ss=7a338&amp;oh=00_Afwj9trgJZNCKIIAkIbhzl39K5kpUGOHMm7-r1c0g-9TFA&amp;oe=69CA207A" alt="Slide 3 fra @semiotexte" style="max-width: 48%; margin: 0 1% 8px 0;" /><img src="https://scontent-cph2-1.cdninstagram.com/v/t51.82787-15/608817215_18093135347485296_8201694544957481064_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_e35_tt6&amp;_nc_cat=104&amp;ig_cache_key=Mzc5OTI4NjcxODczNTIzNjMyMw%3D%3D.3-ccb7-5&amp;ccb=7-5&amp;_nc_sid=58cdad&amp;efg=eyJ2ZW5jb2RlX3RhZyI6InhwaWRzLjkyN3g4Mzguc2RyLkMzIn0%3D&amp;_nc_ohc=bkTkwJnUmyoQ7kNvwFL_kFJ&amp;_nc_oc=Adq7ZIQJm0a5C0ArAaI2DcccQtYQ5fOFB5_GIN844xoYGHFuCoggKEiseO6-TuJ79W4&amp;_nc_ad=z-m&amp;_nc_cid=0&amp;_nc_zt=23&amp;se=8&amp;_nc_ht=scontent-cph2-1.cdninstagram.com&amp;_nc_gid=gasANtv10cnKzYTbI_Jbhw&amp;_nc_ss=7a338&amp;oh=00_AfyHueK0gl2H38XHLUyBIP6Ekj8m55GdG9E8JwlSVtVXQA&amp;oe=69CA2A1D" alt="Slide 4 fra @semiotexte" style="max-width: 48%; margin: 0 1% 8px 0;" /></p><p><strong>🖼️ Slideshow (5 medier)</strong></p><p><strong>@semiotexte</strong></p><p>Thank you Meghan O’Gieblyn for this perceptive and moving review in The New York Times of Natasha Stagg’s coming of age novel, Grand Rapids:<br/>
<br/>
“The novel’s most impressive accomplishment is its rendering of Tess’s grief, which is less an outpouring than a slow bleed into the general anomie of teenage life. Stagg inhabits Tess’s consciousness with a luminous deadpan, a gaze that grasps, without amusement or malice, the garish absurdities of life in West Michigan.” And:<br/>
<br/>
“Stagg, who has described her style as “artless,” is writing against the grain of hyper-stylization and painstaking curation that dominates life in the internet age. The novel ultimately resists the overdetermined escape plot of the bildungsroman, which often recounts an aimless youth in the hinterlands that launches the narrator into a more cosmopolitan life.”</p><p><a href="https://www.instagram.com/p/DS5xybdEkWa/">Se slideshow på Instagram</a></p>]]></content:encoded>
